  "prompt": "What is stannic hydroxide?",
  "response": "Stannic hydroxide is a chemical compound with the formula Sn(OH)4. It is a hydrated form of tin(IV) oxide and has the following characteristics:\n\n1. Composition: It consists of a tin atom bonded to four hydroxyl (OH-) groups.\n\n2. Appearance: Stannic hydroxide typically appears as a white, gelatinous precipitate.\n\n3. Formation: It is usually formed when a soluble tin(IV) salt reacts with a base, such as sodium hydroxide.\n\n4. Properties:\n- Insoluble in water\n- Amphoteric (can react with both acids and bases)\n- Unstable and tends to dehydrate to form tin(IV) oxide\n\n5. Uses: It has limited practical applications but can be used in some chemical processes and as a precursor in the preparation of other tin compounds.\n\nStannic hydroxide is an important intermediate compound in tin chemistry and can be relevant in various industrial and research contexts.",
